IA-64 guest firmware
====================

``ia64-firmware.bin`` is the GPL-2.0-or-later guest-executed PAL/SAL/EFI
firmware baseline from the vendored IA-64 QEMU reference tree:

  vibtanium/external-src/qemu-system-ia64-main/roms/ia64-firmware

The reference tree's QEMU lineage is attributed to
``syunnPC/qemu-system-ia64`` (https://github.com/syunnPC/qemu-system-ia64).
Vibtanium uses that tree as an implementation reference, not as an
architectural oracle: emulator behavior is checked against the IA-64 manuals
and independent guest behavior when the reference and architecture disagree.

The checked-in binary was taken from that tree's
``release-mingw64-lto/share/ia64-firmware.bin`` artifact.  Its SHA-256 is:

  8aa86169bc89739aea4cbfffe78f5f23323c120949e4690936159ce19ff4d2c2

The source uses an IA-64 cross compiler which is not a normal QEMU build
dependency.  Keeping the firmware as an installed pc-bios blob matches the
other architecture firmware artifacts and lets the machine locate it through
``qemu_find_file(QEMU_FILE_TYPE_BIOS, ...)``.

The former host-implemented graphical EFI maintenance front end is not yet
reproduced by this guest firmware.  Its pre-rewrite implementation remains a
user-interface design reference, but any port belongs in guest-executed EFI
firmware rather than in host instruction or service dispatch.

The firmware currently publishes an FPSWA protocol handle only as a visibility
fallback.  Its callback returns the IA-64 ``UNHANDLED`` status and does not
perform floating-point software assist.  Windows boot policy can still depend
on whether this handle is selected or exposed through NVRAM, so automatic
FPSWA boot registration remains incomplete.

``tests/ia64-efi-bit/bit.efi`` is a separately linked IA-64 PE32+ EFI
application, not a host callback blob.  The build installs it as
``vibtanium-bit.efi`` beside the firmware.  ``-Dvibtanium_efi=false`` (or
``--disable-vibtanium-efi``) opts out of packaging both artifacts together.
